<paragraph blockId="20.[1069,1199,1810,1836]" box="[1069,1199,1810,1836]" pageId="20" pageNumber="701">
<heading box="[1069,1199,1810,1836]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="20" pageNumber="701" reason="2">
cf. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gilmore" authorityYear="1909" box="[1102,1199,1810,1836]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphenodontidae" genus="Opisthias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchocephalia" pageId="20" pageNumber="701" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1102,1199,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="701">Opisthias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[1087,1180,1841,1868]" box="[1087,1180,1841,1868]" pageId="20" pageNumber="701">
(
<figureCitation box="[1095,1172,1841,1868]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,739,756]" captionTargetBox="[132,775,215,702]" captionTargetId="figure-803@21.[132,775,207,721]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 14. — Rhynchocephalian right dentary fragment from Angeac-Charente: A-C, cf. Opisthias sp. (ANG M-120) in labial (A), lingual (B) and dorsal (C) views. Scale bar: 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902067/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="701">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[811,1455,1906,2028]" box="[813,957,1906,1932]" pageId="20" pageNumber="701">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[811,1455,1906,2028]" lastBlockId="21.[130,777,853,1613]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="702" pageId="20" pageNumber="701">
ANG M-120 (
<figureCitation box="[965,1039,1937,1963]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,739,756]" captionTargetBox="[132,775,215,702]" captionTargetId="figure-803@21.[132,775,207,721]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 14. — Rhynchocephalian right dentary fragment from Angeac-Charente: A-C, cf. Opisthias sp. (ANG M-120) in labial (A), lingual (B) and dorsal (C) views. Scale bar: 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902067/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="701">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) is a posterior dentary fragment bearing two preserved acrodont teeth in addition to seven broken teeth, there are six anteriorly and one posteriorly.Tooth crowns are sub-pyramidal in shape, angulous anteriorly, more rounded posteriorly, and slightly inclined anteriorly throughout the dentition (
<figureCitation box="[249,349,917,943]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,739,756]" captionTargetBox="[132,775,215,702]" captionTargetId="figure-803@21.[132,775,207,721]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 14. — Rhynchocephalian right dentary fragment from Angeac-Charente: A-C, cf. Opisthias sp. (ANG M-120) in labial (A), lingual (B) and dorsal (C) views. Scale bar: 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902067/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Fig. 14A</figureCitation>
). As suggested by tooth bases, teeth are gradually increasing in size posteriorly. In occlusal view, the tooth row is straight (
<figureCitation box="[358,457,980,1007]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,739,756]" captionTargetBox="[132,775,215,702]" captionTargetId="figure-803@21.[132,775,207,721]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 14. — Rhynchocephalian right dentary fragment from Angeac-Charente: A-C, cf. Opisthias sp. (ANG M-120) in labial (A), lingual (B) and dorsal (C) views. Scale bar: 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902067/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Fig. 14C</figureCitation>
). The coronoid process is broken at its base and the mandibular ramus is broken ventrally at the level of the Meckelian groove (
<figureCitation box="[534,633,1044,1070]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,739,756]" captionTargetBox="[132,775,215,702]" captionTargetId="figure-803@21.[132,775,207,721]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 14. — Rhynchocephalian right dentary fragment from Angeac-Charente: A-C, cf. Opisthias sp. (ANG M-120) in labial (A), lingual (B) and dorsal (C) views. Scale bar: 2.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902067/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Fig. 14B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902067" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6902067" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902067/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" startId="21.[132,143,739,756]" targetBox="[132,775,215,702]" targetPageId="21">
<paragraph blockId="21.[132,777,739,802]" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">
FIG. 14. — Rhynchocephalian right dentary fragment from Angeac-Charente: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,166,762,779]" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">A -C</emphasis>
, cf. 
<taxonomicName box="[200,307,762,779]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphenodontidae" genus="Opisthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchocephalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[200,277,762,779]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Opisthias</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
(ANG M-120) in labial (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[493,506,762,779]" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">A</emphasis>
), lingual (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[583,596,762,779]" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">B</emphasis>
) and dorsal (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[700,714,762,779]" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">C</emphasis>
) views. Scale bar: 2.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="21.[130,777,853,1613]" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">
ANG M-120 is here tentatively referred to cf. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gilmore" authorityYear="1909" box="[678,776,1076,1102]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphenodontidae" genus="Opisthias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchocephalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[678,776,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Opisthias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the tooth morphology and gradual heterodonty pattern which is similar to that observed in previously described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gilmore" authorityYear="1909" box="[130,228,1172,1198]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphenodontidae" genus="Opisthias" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchocephalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[130,228,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Opisthias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
dentaries (
<bibRefCitation author="GILMORE C. W." box="[354,510,1172,1198]" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" pagination="35 - 42" refId="ref40491" refString="GILMORE C. W. 1910 - A new rhynchocephalian reptile from the Jurassic of Wyoming, with notes on the fauna of &quot; Quarry 9 &quot;. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 37: 35 - 42. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.37 - 1698.35" type="journal article" year="1910">Gilmore 1910</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="EVANS S. E. &amp; FRASER N. C." box="[526,758,1172,1198]" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" pagination="199 - 200" refId="ref39343" refString="EVANS S. E. &amp; FRASER N. C. 1992. - A sphenodontid jaw (Reptilia: Lepidosauria) from the Upper Jurassic of Dorset. Proceedings of the Dorset Natural History Society 1992: 199 - 200." type="journal article" year="1992">Evans &amp; Fraser 1992</bibRefCitation>
). In lateral view, the dentary of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyer" authorityYear="1845" box="[478,631,1205,1230]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphenodontidae" genus="Homoeosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchocephalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[478,631,1205,1230]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Homoeosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows wider tooth bases and crown apices that are less acute and not anteriorly inclined (Cocude-Michel 1963). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pallary" authorityYear="1919" box="[609,714,1268,1293]" class="Gastropoda" family="Helicidae" genus="Tingitana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[609,714,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Tingitana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Tihonian-Berriasian of 
<collectingCountry box="[422,523,1300,1326]" name="Morocco" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Morocco</collectingCountry>
, has dentary teeth bearing a strong, inwardly concave, anterolingual crest between a large posterior cone and a small anterolingual one (Evans &amp; Sigogneau-Russell 1997). It is worth noting that a sphenodontian from Cherves-de-Cognac, represented by a partial skeleton, was referred to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyer" authorityYear="1845" box="[415,567,1460,1485]" class="Reptilia" family="Sphenodontidae" genus="Homoeosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rhynchocephalia" pageId="21" pageNumber="702" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[415,567,1460,1485]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">Homoeosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="BUFFETAUT E. &amp; RIGOLLET L. &amp; ARCHAMBEAU J. P." pageId="21" pageNumber="702" pagination="1065 - 1069" refId="ref37014" refString="BUFFETAUT E., POUIT D, RIGOLLET L. &amp; ARCHAMBEAU J. P. 1989. - Poissons et reptiles continentaux du Purbeckien de la region de Cognac (Charente). Bulletin de la Societe geologique de France 5 (5): 1065 - 1069. https: // doi. org / 10.2113 / gssgfbull. V. 5.1065" type="journal article" year="1989">
Buffetaut 
<emphasis box="[721,775,1459,1485]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="702">et al.</emphasis>
1989
</bibRefCitation>
. A revision of this material, housed in a private collection, including a detailed comparison with the Angeac- Charente specimen would be useful to assess sphenodontian diversity in western Europe.
</paragraph>
